<DOC><DOCNO> AP880309-0362 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 0142EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-09 0510</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0531</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   R.H. Macy andamp; Co. Inc. has begun its $6.1 billiontender offer for Federated Department Stores Inc. and has gone tocourt in hopes of torpedoing the competing $6.18 billion offer byCampeau Corp.   Macy filed suit Tuesday in federal court in Manhattan seeking aninjunction to bar Campeau from proceeding with its tender offer onthe grounds that Campeau's amended bid was actually a new offer andas such must remain open beyond its scheduled expiration atmidnight March 15.   Extending Campeau's bid would reduce the pressure on Federatedshareholders to decide between the rival Macy and Campeau offers,effectively putting the Macy offer _ which expires April 4 _ onbetter footing.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Higher stamp prices won't take effect untilnext month at the earliest, postal officials say.   The board of governors of the U.S. Postal Service decidedTuesday to postpone a final decision on the effective date of thenew rates, and scheduled a special meeting for March 22 to discussputting the new rates into effect, effectively delaying theincrease until April 3 at the earliest.   The new prices, recommended by the independent Postal RateCommission last Friday, would boost the first-class rate to 25cents from 22 cents.</TEXT><DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Dart Group Corp. has abandoned its $1.03billion takeover bid for Stop andamp; Shop Cos. and says it will returnall tendered shares to Stop andamp; Shop stockholders.   Stop andamp; Shop announced on Feb. 29 it had agreed to be acquired ina $1.23 billion leveraged buyout by the investment firm of KohlbergKravis Roberts Inc.   Dart's tender offer expires at midnight Wednesday and will notbe extended, Dart said Tuesday in a one-paragraph announcement.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal appellate panel has upheld a lowercourt's finding that there was no evidence General Motors Corp.knowingly sold 1.1 million 1980 X-cars with alleged brake defects.   The panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Tuesdayaffirmed U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's 1987rejection of government claims that the cars had an inherent defectthat caused rear brakes to lock up prematurely and spin out ofcontrol under certain circumstances.</TEXT><DATELINE>LIVONIA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co. has handed thousands ofprofit-sharing checks to U.S. workers as their share of thecompany's industry record profit of $4.6 billion for 1987.   Ford distributed $653 million in profit-sharing checks Tuesdayaveraging more than $3,700 to 156,479 hourly and salaried workers.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Cheating on federal income taxes has declinedby as much as 20 percent, mainly because of tax law changes andtougher federal policing, Internal Revenue Service CommissionerLawrence B. Gibbs says.   Gibbs told a House Appropriations subcommittee on Tuesday thatan IRS study indicates the difference between taxes owed and taxespaid has dropped to between $80 billion and $90 billion in 1987.The agency's last report on the annual gap estimated it would riseto more than $100 billion in 1987.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>